{"title_page": "Sp\u012bn Ghar", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{about|the mountain range|the cricket team|Speen Ghar Tigers}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n|name='''Safed Koh'''\n|map_image=\n|map_size=\n|photo=Khogyani district.jpg\n|photo_size=\n|photo_caption=Safed Koh starting from [[Tora Bora|Eastern Afghanistan]] to deep [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], Pakistan.\n|other_name={{lang-fa|\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u062f\u06a9\u0648\u0647 (Saf\u0113d K\u014dh)}}; {{lang-en|Safed Koh, Indian Caucasus}} \n|country=[[Afghanistan]]\n|country1=[[Pakistan]]\n|region_type=Provinces\n|region=[[Nangarhar Province]], [[Afghanistan]]|region1=[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]]\n|range_coordinates = \n|parent=\n|geology=\n|period=\n|orogeny=\n|highest=[[Mount Sikaram]]\n|highest_location= [[Afghanistan]]\u2013[[Pakistan]] Border\n|elevation={{convert|4761|m|ft|0|lk=off|abbr=on}} \n|coordinates = \n|length_km=\n|length_note=([[great-circle distance|straight-line distance]])\n|length_ref=\n}}\n'''Saf\u0113d K\u014dh'''<ref name=\"Britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/516155/Safid-Mountain-Range Saf\u012bd Mountain Range] in [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], 2009</ref><ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Safed Koh |volume=23 |pages=994\u2013995}}</ref><ref>[https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199580897.001.0001/acref-9780199580897-e-9128 Oxford dictionary]</ref><ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/cia-rdp96-00792r000700280001-0 CIA]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.cz/books?id=JqM7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA578&lpg=PA578&dq=safed+koh&source=bl&ots=8t6-1nxL2t&sig=ACfU3U2X4pycVZoxPMJE45-irUFgn16aQQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjuh8P5zIHpAhUKmhQKHXEeC-44HhDoATADegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=safed%20koh&f=false older sources]</ref>  ([[Persian language|Persian]]: {{lang|fa|\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u062f\u06a9\u0648\u0647}}, meaning \"white mountain\" in Persian) is a [[mountain range]] in eastern [[Afghanistan]], which expands into [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]].  Its highest peak, straight and rigid [[Mount Sikaram]], towers above all surrounding hills to {{convert|4761|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} [[above mean sea level]]. Some parts of these mountains, mainly [[Tora Bora]] caves are called 'Sp\u012bn Ghar'  ({{lang-ps|\u0633\u067e\u064a\u0646 \u063a\u0631}}) by local Pashtun tribes.<ref>[https://www.defense.gov/observe/photo-gallery/igphoto/2001152364/ defense.gov]</ref>\n\nThe [[Kabul River]] cuts a narrow [[Trough (geology)|trough]] through the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh mountains to flow eastward into the [[Indus River]]; otherwise, the range connects directly with the [[Shandur Top]] offshoot of the [[Hindu Kush]] mountain system.<ref name=\"Britannica\" />  The closest cities to the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh are [[Jalalabad]], [[Afghanistan]] to the north; [[Gardez]], [[Paktia Province]], [[Afghanistan]] to the west; and [[Khost]], [[Khost Province]], [[Afghanistan]] and [[Parachinar]], [[Kurram District]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] province, [[Pakistan]] to the south.  From the highest peak of the [[mountain range]], ([[Mount Sikaram|Mount Sikaram (Sikaram Sar)]]), eastward, it passes on the north of Parachamkani, [[Afghanistan]]; [[Tari Mangal]], [[Pewar]], [[Alizai, Kurram|Alizai]], Khewas, Shilawzan, Luqman Khel, Maikay, Chappri Rest House, Zeran,  and Upper Khyber Agency. \n\nThere are a few notable [[mountain pass|mountain passes]] in or near the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh [[mountain range]].  The famous [[Khyber Pass]] crosses a spur of the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh.  A second crossing, near [[Mount Sikaram]], is called Piewar-Kotal or Gawi Pass and connects [[Parachinar]] city in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas with the [[Aryob]] Valley of [[Paktia Province]], Afghanistan. \n\nIt is situated in the East of 'Dra Khebar'.\n\nAbove the nearly barren lower slopes, forests of pine and [[Cedrus deodara|deodar cedar]] thrived on the main range, but devastation during the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|Afghan civil war]] reduced timber resources.  The valleys still support some agriculture.\n\nAccording to [[United States|US]] military intelligence, many al-Qaeda fighters, including [[Osama Bin Laden]], crossed the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh to escape to Pakistan during the [[Battle of Tora Bora|Tora Bora offensive]] in 2001. After 2004, the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh mountain range was a pivotal place and theater of many battles fought between the [[Foreign Mujahideen|foreign fighters]] of [[al-Qaeda]] and the joint [[War in North-West Pakistan order of battle|Northern Command]] of the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani military]], with the latter trying to prevent the [[Foreign Mujahideen|foreign fighters]]' incursion into Pakistan.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mountain ranges]] of the world\n* [[List of highest mountains]] (a list of mountains above 7,200m)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|33|58|N|70|22|E|display=title|region:PK_type:mountain_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sp\u012bn Ghar}}\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:War in North-West Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Paktia Province]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Afghanistan-geo-stub}}\n{{Pakistan-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{about|the mountain range|the cricket team|Speen Ghar Tigers}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n|name='''Safed Koh'''\n|map_image=\n|map_size=\n|photo=Khogyani district.jpg\n|photo_size=\n|photo_caption=Safed Koh starting from [[Tora Bora|Eastern Afghanistan]] to deep [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], Pakistan.\n|other_name={{lang-fa|\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0648\u0647 (Saf\u0113d K\u014dh)}}; {{lang-en|Safed Koh, Indian Caucasus}} \n|country=[[Afghanistan]]\n|country1=[[Pakistan]]\n|region_type=Provinces\n|region=[[Nangarhar Province]], [[Afghanistan]]|region1=[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]]\n|range_coordinates = \n|parent=\n|geology=\n|period=\n|orogeny=\n|highest=[[Mount Sikaram]]\n|highest_location= [[Afghanistan]]\u2013[[Pakistan]] Border\n|elevation={{convert|4761|m|ft|0|lk=off|abbr=on}} \n|coordinates = \n|length_km=\n|length_note=([[great-circle distance|straight-line distance]])\n|length_ref=\n}}\n'''Saf\u0113d K\u014dh'''<ref name=\"Britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/516155/Safid-Mountain-Range Saf\u012bd Mountain Range] in [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], 2009</ref><ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Safed Koh |volume=23 |pages=994\u2013995}}</ref><ref>[https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199580897.001.0001/acref-9780199580897-e-9128 Oxford dictionary]</ref><ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/cia-rdp96-00792r000700280001-0 CIA]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.cz/books?id=JqM7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA578&lpg=PA578&dq=safed+koh&source=bl&ots=8t6-1nxL2t&sig=ACfU3U2X4pycVZoxPMJE45-irUFgn16aQQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjuh8P5zIHpAhUKmhQKHXEeC-44HhDoATADegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=safed%20koh&f=false older sources]</ref>  ([[Persian language|Persian]]: {{lang|fa|\u0633\u0641\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0648\u0647}}, meaning \"white mountain\" in Persian) is a [[mountain range]] in eastern [[Afghanistan]], which expands into [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pakistan]].  Its highest peak, straight and rigid [[Mount Sikaram]], towers above all surrounding hills to {{convert|4761|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} [[above mean sea level]]. Some parts of these mountains, mailny [[Tora Bora]] caves are called 'Sp\u012bn Ghar'  ({{lang-ps|\u0633\u067e\u064a\u0646 \u063a\u0631}}) by local Pashtun tribes.<ref>[https://www.defense.gov/observe/photo-gallery/igphoto/2001152364/ defense.gov]</ref>\n\nThe [[Kabul River]] cuts a narrow [[Trough (geology)|trough]] through the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh mountains to flow eastward into the [[Indus River]]; otherwise, the range connects directly with the [[Shandur Top]] offshoot of the [[Hindu Kush]] mountain system.<ref name=\"Britannica\" />  The closest cities to the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh are [[Jalalabad]], [[Afghanistan]] to the north; [[Gardez]], [[Paktia Province]], [[Afghanistan]] to the west; and [[Khost]], [[Khost Province]], [[Afghanistan]] and [[Parachinar]], [[Kurram District]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] province, [[Pakistan]] to the south.  From the highest peak of the [[mountain range]], ([[Mount Sikaram|Mount Sikaram (Sikaram Sar)]]), eastward, it passes on the north of Parachamkani, [[Afghanistan]]; [[Tari Mangal]], [[Pewar]], [[Alizai, Kurram|Alizai]], Khewas, Shilawzan, Luqman Khel, Maikay, Chappri Rest House, Zeran,  and Upper Khyber Agency. \n\nThere are a few notable [[mountain pass|mountain passes]] in or near the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh [[mountain range]].  The famous [[Khyber Pass]] crosses a spur of the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh.  A second crossing, near [[Mount Sikaram]], is called Piewar-Kotal or Gawi Pass and connects [[Parachinar]] city in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas with the [[Aryob]] Valley of [[Paktia Province]], Afghanistan. \n\nIt is situated in the East of 'Dra Khebar'.\n\nAbove the nearly barren lower slopes, forests of pine and [[Cedrus deodara|deodar cedar]] thrived on the main range, but devastation during the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|Afghan civil war]] reduced timber resources.  The valleys still support some agriculture.\n\nAccording to [[United States|US]] military intelligence, many al-Qaeda fighters, including [[Osama Bin Laden]], crossed the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh to escape to Pakistan during the [[Battle of Tora Bora|Tora Bora offensive]] in 2001. After 2004, the Saf\u0113d K\u014dh mountain range was a pivotal place and theater of many battles fought between the [[Foreign Mujahideen|foreign fighters]] of [[al-Qaeda]] and the joint [[War in North-West Pakistan order of battle|Northern Command]] of the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani military]], with the latter trying to prevent the [[Foreign Mujahideen|foreign fighters]]' incursion into Pakistan.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mountain ranges]] of the world\n* 